@node "gr4" "Max Rally"

@{fg shine} Max Rally@{fg text}

 MAX Rally comes on two disks with shiny labels, in its own C.D style
case. When you first open the case disk 1 will most proberly fall out,
because the case seems to be made for one disk, and not two!

 MAX Rally is a multi-player overhead racing game for all Amigas with at
least 2 Meg of memory. Up to four players can participate in various
types of race, against each other, against the clock or against
intelligent computer controlled cars?

 MAX Rally will install on your Hard Drive, but if you only have 2mb of
memory (Guess who?) you will have to load the game, by going through the
early startup controls and loading the program though DOS.

 After loading you are presented with a little introduction and you get
to see the 3D MAX Rally logo. It looks great, but its the game I'm
revewing here!

 There are various games you can play; a one-player (only) challenge,
where you have to win all of the 21 tracks, in 5 continues, but you can
get more continues by atempting the MAX Challenges; next is multi-player,
which lets you play 2 or 4 player battle mode, or a 2-player race (4
player with two Amiga's and a null-modem cable). Last up is Time Trials,
where you must race on your own, trying to beat previous records, or in
multi-player against the other players.

 There are 4 different terrains; Woodland Rally, Cosmic, Alpine, and the
Fortress Dunes. These can be played in any order on the challenge, and
you can race on any track in the multi-player and time-trials. It would
be good if you had some 'locked' tracks, which you can only get to after
winning so many other tracks. In my opinion this would make the game a
bit more exciting.

 The cosmic terrain is the most leaful, the other three terrains are
fairly bog-standard, nice graphics, but you have no freedom of movement,
you are boxed inside the track, you can not venture out to explore the
scenary. And what chance have you got in hitting the bounderies? Hardly
anything, because at either side of the track there is grass, or snow,
which slows you down, but on a track in the woodland rally you have to
go off the track, but you are still locked in! With Cosmic, for most of
the track you are locked in, but at some points, you can fall off!!
Arrgg! This is quite annoying, when you are participating in a MAX Rally
challenge you could fall off and you lose a continue, particually
annoying when you do a really bad jump, but never fear, becuase you can
cut jumps short by holding DOWN (in fearie).

 On the originally titled Track 2, of Cosmic, you may find computer cars
get stuck, well, they keep running into the track bounderies. Its lucky
its not real life, because their cars wouldn't be much good after such a
battering. However, if you do find a computer car hitting the walls
leave it alone, and it will stay there, and you have no fear of coming
last.

 The cosmic levels seem to dominate the game, there are 5 tracks, of
woodland, alpine, and dunes, but the desciption on the case says there
are 26 tracks. That means there are 11 cosmic tracks!!! The cars look
much better with cosmic, I can't describe why, they just are. I think
MAX Rally was only going to have cosmic tracks in its eary stage of
development, and the other terrains were added later?

 Back to the menu, there are some more options, you can customise the
drivers names, be cafeful though, because each driver is serpost to
have varying abilities, which are hard to spot, to say the least! You
can also view pre-recorded demos, which are impossible to copy. You can
change the difficultly level, it defaults to EASY, but put it on hard
and the cars will go super fast, but they will be harder to control.
Another problem with EASY, is the simple fact, it is easy, most of
the tracks can be completed first time, you need no skill what so
ever.

 Well, whats the game like? Its really good, the lap times and postition
text is sometimes distorted, but that doesn't interfere with the
gameplay. The screen scrolls very smoothly, and in HARD mode you can
really get some speed up, and thats what you really want from a top-down
racer. The different terrains have there own features, but they all have
big and small jumps, off which you can do a 360° spin in the air and
skid around corners with real speed, this is all fine, but in reality,
it is impossible to get right. Another amazing feature of the smaller
jumps, is that when you look at them the seem to point into the air
( / ), but in pratice, they are not, you can jump off them in any
direction!

 The only exciting 1 player mode is the challenge, you get 5 continues
and you must finish first on all of the tracks. The tracks are rated
using stars, 1 star is easy, and 5 stars is very difficult. If you want
more continues you can either lap everyone (quite simple on EASY mode) or
atempt a MAX Challenge, here you must complete three laps, without going
off the edge of the screen, and without falling off the side of the
track. There are various pads, placed around the tracks; moving pads,
which transport your car between different areas of the track; lap
pads; and switch pads. At the start of each lap, all switch pads are
switched on, that is, lit up. In order to complete a lap, they must all
be switched off, by driving over them. When this is done, a lap pad will
be lit up, and this must then be switched off to complete the lap. When
the lap pad is switched off, all switch pads are turned back on for
another lap. If a pad is missed, the lap has to be done again. Extra
continues are awarded for completing the entire track without missing a
pad. Set in the cosmic terrain (again) the screen scrolls independantly
of the main car, making the challenges impossible, even the 1 star
challenge is hard!

 What ever game mode you are doing, you always get one turbo per race,
it is pointless having one, it makes you go a little bit faster for a
few seconds! You can turn turbos off in the options. If you want?

 MAX Rally will let you save and load your record times, this would be a
good idea if to select the file you didn't have to use the Blitz Basic
requester (Yuk!) Another point, you can merge two sets of records
together, so you could battle it out with you friends for the world
record!

 The challenge is cool, the only annoying parts are when you have to
repeat all the tracks again, because you failed a MAX Challenge! And the
unchangable 12 laps are a pain in the back side! It would be better with
music, but the brilliant quality music won't load on my 2 meg A1200, but
it sounds good in OctaMED SoundStudio.

 And now some anoying things, you can only do each track once, in 2
player race, you get an anoying beat all the way through the race, but
despite these little things, the challenge is wonderful!?

 Another mode is multi-player, you can have up to 4 players racing at a
time, either with a two player joystick adaptor, where you are limited
to battle mode (in 4 player), or by using a null-modem cable and two
Amiga's running MAX Rally at the same time.

 Two player race is great, but it doesn't compare to the battle mode,
where you have to race against each other on a single screen. The
idea of this race is to get your car to the front of the screen, while
the screen is scrolling round following all the cars. Falling off the
back of the screen results in your car being taken off the track until
someone else has won a point. Points are gained by staying on the screen
until all other cars have been eliminated. The winner of the race is the
first player to gain five points. This is really fun, you are competing
with your friends, and not your computer. Its really competitive, but
its really boring if your the first person to be taken off the track.
Doesn't this remind you of Micro Machines?

 Battle mode is much better than the multi-player time-trials, for a start
you have your own controller (in time-trials you have to share). Its fun
racing against each other, atempting to get the best time is boring!

 Throughout my intence testing I did discover some vital bugs, if you
fall off on a cosmic time-trial, you start again from where you left
off. Fine, but the clock stops, you don't complete laps as far as the
computer is concenered, and you'll most proberly get a new lap record!

 Overall MAX Rally is really fun to play, its quite addictive at first,
but its lastability lets it down in the long run. A good effot, I want
to see more of this around.

