@node "gr5" "NIM"

@{fg shine} NIM, Simple sticks game@{fg text}

 Nim is serposidly a old game invented by the Japanese, basically there
is a pile of matchsticks, and 2 players. Each player takes turns in taking
an amount of matchsticks, and the player who removes the last matchstick
is the loser. In this game one player is human, the other is the computer.

 The game runs in the shell, which may seem a little disapointing at
first, but the game would run to better in it's own window. Anyway, the
game is one of the authors early C++ assignments!

 The game is the simplest thing ever, if the Japanese version wasn't
based on matchsticks kids would be playing this the world over! Maybe
not?

 First of all you enter how many matchsticks you want to start with,
then you enter the maxium number to be taken per go, for example,
entering 100 and 50 would give a reasonable game. Now decide who is to go
first, the computer, or the human, and then you take it in turns to take
as many matchsticks as you want (not acceeding the limit of course).

 It seems to me that the computer has the ability to take 0 matchsticks,
but you have to take at least 1. Ummmm!? I also think the limit on the
amount of matchsticks you can have is 2147483646, it is anoying when you
put in more than that, because the computer excepts the higher number,
and when you set the limit to anything greater than 2147483646 the
computer leaves you with one matchstick. Gutted!

 If you get bored with the game, you can't just close the shell, you
have to finish the game, this is very anoying, especially when you have
230717627 matchsticks left.

 In the end, this is simple, and great to amuse the kids (or big kids)
for a short time (before it's time for tea, or sommit). It would be nice
if there was a two player game as well, it could even be in its own
window or screen?

