@node "ur3" "Clipboard History"

@{fg shine} ClipHistory v2.4@{fg text}

  Do you have one of these? I didn't. I had realised that I needed a clipboard
history utility about a month before actually getting around to downloading
one :) But now I regret that I waited so long, because this is such a great
program that I couldn't live without it any more :) For example when I read an
URL somewhere and I want to visit it but can't just yet, I don't have to
scribble it on some piece of paper; I'll just copy it to the clipboard and
when the time comes I'll select it from the history window and paste it to my
browser.

  I can't recall if I picked this one at random or if it was the newest clip
history program in Aminet, but since it has all the functionality that I can
ever need, I haven't bothered to test other programs :) Examples of the
useful features: it has an ARexx port with about 40 commands, you can freely
define the hotkeys for the "blind" selection of the next/previous clip
(without the window popping up), it can open even on non-public screens, it
can close the window after selecting a clip entry, you can choose the clip
with one or two clicks, you can set the maximum number of clips held in
memory, it can reject too big or small clips (especially useful for PowerSnap
users), it can check if the new clip is a copy of the latest (or any) entry in
memory and not store it twice, you can filter out (or in) any IFF types and of
course save any clip to a file.

  ClipHistory has an installer script, so the most tedious part of installing
is that you have to configure all the options :) But when you're done you'll
see that it was worth the time and effort, because it will behave exactly as
you wanted it to and using it will be swift and easy.

  ClipHistory requires only AmigaOS 2.04, but it will utilise OS 3.0 features
and ReqTools. It is also completely system friendly and won't patch any
library functions (unless you want it to open on non-public screens). What can
I say, it's just amazing! :)

