@node "ur4" "Day Utils"

@{fg shine} DayCopy, DayDelete, DayList, DayMove@{fg text}

  These utilities are for copying, deleting, listing and moving files that are
older or younger than the given number of days. At least for me they are quite
useful, since I always have loads of files in my downloads drawer (currently
almost 450 :). Especially DayList will come in handy, since I often need to
see the files downloaded today or 3 days ago or something like that. The
standard "list" command has the "since" parameter but it only accepts "today",
"yesterday" and dd-mmm-yy, and I don't have time to think what day it was 3
days ago ;)

  All the 4 commands have a similar command template: number of days, source
dir, destination dir (for copy and move), "older" switch (affect files older
than the given number of days), "quiet" switch and "all" switch (recurse into
subdirectories).

  So, for example when I want to see the files downloaded in the past 4 days,
I'll write: "daylist 4 work:downloads", or to delete files older than 30 days:
"daydelete 30 work:downloads older".

  Unfortunately the author hasn't thought about the template too carefully;
the number of days isn't required but the source dir is. So if I want to list
some files in the current directory, I'll have to write:  daylist 3 ""
That's one big con, and another is that it outputs only one filename per line,
so if it finds 50 files for example, it will output 50 (plus a few) lines
instead of them all fitting very nicely in even a small Shell window as the
"ls" command would list them...

