@node "ur5" "Image Engineer"

@{fg shine} Image Engineer v3.41@{fg text}

  This image processing utility was a positive surprise to me. After
downloading both the LHA archives (just a bit over 1 MB total) I realised that
it needs the SuperView package. And I had deleted it just a few weeks ago
(there's a quick review for you ;), so back to downloading again. Then I
installed them both and launched Image Engineer with no clear idea of what to
expect...

  After about 15 seconds of loading I had a pretty clear image in my mind.
Another 15 and it finally did something visible and let me choose the screen
mode (yes, this *is* a slow machine but I would've expected no more than 15
seconds.. :). IE uses BGUI so the GUI isn't too beautiful, but it works and
all the windows are resizable so it'll do. IE requires at least a 640*400
screenmode and you can choose any number of colours for it. After selecting,
it opened the screen and displayed the shareware requester (unregistered will
only handle images up to 400*400 pixels in size, 35 USD to register). Then I
only had to adjust a few settings and I was ready to start using it.

  I noticed quickly that all the image processing in IE is *very* fast, and
that's because 98% of it is coded in 68020 optimized assembler. Too bad that
this means that 040, 060 and PPC support would be really difficult to add
(at least I think so :). All the image processing modules have stamp-size
preview boxes (either a selectable part of the image or the whole image
scaled down) and they update very fast too when you're adjusting the various
sliders and gadgets. IE is also quite memory efficient, which is hard not to
notice on this low-mem machine of mine :)

  IE has CyberGraphX support as well as native Amiga modes (including the
HAM6 and HAM8 modes, but not for the preview ("edit") screen). It can process
images in 24 bit color or 8 bit grayscale, and it supports all the image
formats that SuperView supports for loading and saving (yes, including JPEG,
PNG and GIF :). You can have multiple images open at the same time and also
re-calculate the best palette for the preview screen to show the opened images
in more "useful" colors. It's just too bad you can't get the default palette
back; if you have a mostly blue image and the palette optimized for it, and
you change its hue to green it won't appear to change much in the thumbnail
preview because all the colors will be shades of blue... You can also zoom
in/out on the preview windows.

  IE has around 40 image processing modules and more to be released in the
future. Here are some of the palette balancing modules: brightness, gamma,
hue, threshold, contrast, negative and saturation, and some filters: median,
highboost, highpass, lowpass, sharpen and convolve (with loads of matrixes,
that can also be transferred to/from PPaint for example). And then there are
the modules that "really" change the image (all of them have "color average"
options): bulge, twirl, ripple, remove feature (collapse), scale and rotate.
And the motion/rotate/zoom blurs make nice effects too...

  Of course, IE has an ARexx interface with many effects scripts supplied.
It has fully configurable menus, with definable keyboard shortcuts too. You
can render images using your own palette, or have it generate the best
possible palette for you (you can also set the number of colors to be used,
and it has several error diffusion algorithms, e.g. Floyd-Steinberg.

  I can't find many bad things to say about IE; the startup-time is long but
it's just because it's loading all the SuperView files (if you quit it and
restart without a memory flush in between, it'll be a lot faster). Then
there's one bug that can sometimes be very bothering; you can't abort loading
an image, even when there's an abort gadget... but at least I didn't encounter
any other bugs! Let's give the author Simon Edwards applause for that :)

