@node "ur6" "YAM Pre 6"

@{fg shine} YAM v2.0 preview 6@{fg text}

  Version 2.0 of the freeware email program YAM is at beta stage currently,
but anyone can download the preview version from the YAM web site. It is a
huge step forward from the latest non-beta version v1.3.5, especially the
user interface. And although it is a preview, it still has more working and
useful features than v1.3.x (and most features do work :)

  Installation is really easy with the installer script and configuration is
very straightforward too. The GUI is very practical; in the main window you
have a list of folders and a list of messages, and a toolbar that lets you
handle your mail (read, write, delete etc.), send and receive mail and do
searches. When writing a message, it's really easy to add/remove file
attachments and to adjust various options for that particular mail, including
the From: field that used to be so difficult to change. The GUI can be
modified flexibly, and the most important part: it's multithreaded, so while
you are writing a message you can also read messages and adjust the settings,
for example (don't you just hate the "wait" mouse pointer ;)

  At start YAM has 4 folders; incoming, outgoing, sent and deleted. It's very
easy to add folders, and adding filters for automatic actions towards the
downloaded messages (e.g. move to a folder) shouldn't be too hard after
reading that section of the guide. The 'deleted' folder is very handy since
messages aren't really deleted instantly after clicking delete (which might
have been an accident) but moved into this folder.

  YAM has various other little features that make it very nice to use. The
address book has a birthday field; YAM can check on every startup if it's
somebody's birthday and remind you about it :) Almost every window has a
toolbar. You can drag & drop messages between folders, and add attachments to
messages by dragging files from Workbench. You can configure it to download
messages automatically at set intervals, and it can automatically strip the
signature when replying to a message. It supports multi-line taglines and
address aliases too (send to 'jack' for example -> turns into Jack's email
address automagically), just to scratch the surface :)

  So what's bad about it? Well, at least it seems to hog a big part of my
measily 8 MB fastmem, and I honestly can't see what it needs it for :) Then
there are a couple of minor bugs; you can't close any windows while
downloading messages, and there's something wrong with aborting the message
download... if you click Abort, it thinks that you don't want that particular
mail and deletes it from the server; with luck you might get a "message stub"
in your incoming folder but it might be a lot smaller than what you had
downloaded so far...

  YAM's bugs are few and insignificant, while it has a lot of features and is
very nice in use... and it's FREE! :) To me this preview was a bit of a let-
down as an upgrade from the previous preview, but at least it's still
evolving! :) I'll remain eagerly awaiting the next preview.. :)

