@node "fe1" "Interview"

@{fg shine} Interview with Oliver Kastl@{fg text}

 This month we had a chat with Oliver Kastl, the man behind IDEFix,
he also runs his own company called Elaborate Bytes. Anyone else
you'd like to see interviewed? email us at @{b}amiga@thefree.net@{ub} and let
us know.

CS : As with all AIO interviews can you firstly tell us who you are and
a little bit about yourself?

OK : Sure. My full name is Oliver Kastl, I was born in Essen (Ruhr-Area), 
Germany. I am pretty old (34, to be precise) and I am in the Amiga 
business since 1986 - phew, this is 12 years! I currently live in a small 
village near Munich together with my wife Frauke and my daughter Lara. 
Beside of my activities as an active Amiga Developer and running Elaborate 
Bytes, I am a father (a very demanding job and my favourite hobby!) and 
work part time as a senior design engineer for a company called Optimay 
GmbH, a subsidiary of Lucent technologies. This is necessary, as Amiga 
development no longer earns enough to pay the bills :-)

CS : How does it feel when you know you have brought CD-rom joy to
many Amiga users around the world?

OK : Great! It is nice to do something useful and make people happy - and earn 
money with it, too. And I didn't only brought CD-Rom joy to a lot of 
people, but Harddisk joy, too. Probably some of you remember the A.L.F. 
hand Oktagon series of Harddisk controllers?

CS : What is it like being instantly recognised when you go places?
for instance on the AIO JUST-AMiGA mailing list someone noticed you
and titled you 'Mr. IDEfix himself'.

OK : Unless the person immediately asks "why does CD-Rom XYZ not work with 
IDE-fix" it makes me feel proud :-) Some years ago when I went to an Amiga 
fair, someone approached me, gave me his hand and said: "I just want to 
hold your hand". Weird, but fun :-)

CS : How did you come up with the idea for IDEfix? and was there anyone
in particular that without, IDEfix could not of happend?

OK : The idea for IDE-fix was the same idea I had with the original ALF ST-506 
controllers: With little hardware and a lot of clever software connecting 
cheap mass storage devices from the PC world to the Amiga. Back in 1986 
there already were SCSI Harddisks for the Amiga, but A.L.F. was the major 
breakthrough, because it allowed to use cheap ST-506 harddisks. The same 
idea was used on the TandemCD and CD1200 controllers, which could use 
cheap Mitsumi CD-Roms. Later, when ATAPI CD-Roms replaced the Mitsumi 
drives, the CD1200+, AlfaPower+, IDE-fix and the Buddha controllers were 
the logical next step.
Andreas Selle (who has written the drivers for the MFC multi I/O cards, 
btw) and Volker Klein (who developed the Oktagon 2008 and Memory Master 
hardware) helped me in the very beginning writing C and efficient 68k 
assembler code. Well, actually they teached me good programming :-)
The CacheCDFS FileSystem which was developed for all my CD-Rom products 
wouldn't be possible without Ralph Babel's Amiga Guru book. Well done, 
Ralph!

CS : What is your happiest Amiga memory so far of 1998?

OK : There were quite some nice memories, but these are rather personal and not 
of public interest, like the contact to other developers. I am pretty 
excited about the announcements Amiga, Inc. has made, like the Amiga 
NextGen or the OS3.5. I don't know if they will succeed, let's wait and 
see.

CS : What do you think was the best year for you on the Amiga and why?

OK : The best years were way back in 1986 - 1990. The Amiga was "the" magic 
machine, with capabilities other computers didn't have. The games were 
outstanding! There were Developer conferences, the machine and technology 
was new, all this was very exciting! I founded Elaborate Bytes as a 
start-up company, which was the basis for all I've done yet.
The greatest moment was when I met Jay G. "Father of the Amiga - Padre" 
Miner who I had the luck to talk to on a Developer's conference in Paris. 
I can't remember what year it was. I had an ALF-II SCSI controller with me 
and a copy of my program "The Jay Miner Connection", which was never 
released to the public, so it could be around 1989. "The Jay Miner 
Connection" was a program and a little cable to connect an 8-Bit ATARI 
(400/800/...) to the Amiga - connecting two of Jay's great machines. I 
asked him for permission to use his name and he agreed. And he told me 
some really funny stories...
He invited me to his home whenever I pass by, but I didn't made it. Sigh.


CS : Why did you choose the Amiga as your computer of choice?

OK : Before I bought an Amiga long, long time ago, I had a Sinclair Spectrum, 
a Sinclair QL and an Atari 800. Then there was the Amiga, and it simply blew 
away the competition. A must have! A computer fun to use and fun to 
develop for, and the Amiga just came like a present from heaven. It only 
lacked a harddisk, so I started developing A.L.F. The rest is history....


CS : What would you like to see happen to the Amiga in the future?

OK : I want to see the plans of Amiga, Inc. become reality. And I wish they 
are  successful. This is tough, so good luck. The Amiga has a difficult 
position nowadays, as it no longer "blows away the competition". There are 
PCs with great games, consoles like N64, Playstation, Saturn, Dreamcast, 
etc., Macs, Linux, BeOS. The current "classic" Amiga can't compete with 
those systems, and the PowerPC Amiga still lacks software and the PPC 
integration into the OS is miles away from Apple's Mac. And Apple isn't 
sleeping, the new MacOS 10 and even the BeOS look very promising. Even 
Microsoft has learned, and Win98 and WinNT aren't as bad as most people 
say. WinCE tries to conquer the embedded market, a market Amiga, Inc. is 
aiming at, too.
So, Amiga, Inc. has a lot of homework to do. They need to integrate all 
those gimmicks the others have into the new OS. All those 3rd party 
enhancements (like IDE-fix) shouldn't be no longer necessary. This might 
hurt me as a developer, but as a user, I would be happy!
I really hope Amiga, Inc. manage to make it in time, as the development of 
a new OS from scratch is a VERY demanding task. I don't know if they will, 
as even companies with high budgets for software development like Apple, 
Be or Microsoft need several years for development a brand new OS.

CS : What specs would you like to see the new Amigas have?

OK : I can't tell you, but it must be as outstanding as the A1000 was 12 years 
ago. Otherwise it wouldn't be the "magic" machine I would call an Amiga, 
but just another PC/Mac/BeBox. It should be something "completely 
different" and "outstanding" again. Probably with a new concept of User 
Interface? Something radically new and different, so people will jump on 
the new Amiga. If I only knew, what this could be, I would be a rich man! 
:-)
I personally would like to see an OS which is fun to program for, but this 
doesn't make sense, if the machine doesn't attract a wide user base. I 
want a machine with graphic and 3D capabilities that "blow your mind away" 
and with a DSP for real-time Audio processing. I would expect that the raw 
CPU and FPU horsepower is satisfying anyway :-)

CS : What do you think is a good point about the Amiga community and
the people in it on a whole and a bad point about us?

OK : The good point: They are fanatics.
The bad point: They are fanatics.
Sometime I have the feeling Amiga is no longer a computer but a religion 
:-)
On the other hand, it is amazing how the Amiga people unite and defend 
their platform and the people developing for it. I have never seen a "anti 
piracy - help the developers" campaign coming from the user base on any 
other platform. This could be worth a sociological study - who are these 
people? why are they doing this? - but this is another story.

CS : Do you think you have received the feedback and payment you
expected for making such a big project as IDEfix?

OK : Yes, I think so. IDE-fix was designed modular, so the code basis could 
be  put in several products like the Individual Computer's Buddha and 
Catweasel, Eyetech's EZ-IDE, Vesalia's WinnerCD or the Telmex EasyCD. What 
nobody knows - a cut down version of CacheCDFS was shipped with Amiga 
Technologies' Q-Drive before Escom went bankrupt...
But remember - parts of IDE-fix are very old! E.g., CacheCDFS was 
developed back in 1993 for the TandemCD and was constantly improved. The 
latest addition was Win95/98 long filename support (Joliet).
Developing a product like IDE-fix now from scratch would not be possible 
(if you expect to get your investment back).
The shareware sales of IDE-fix '97 could definitely be much higher, even 
with this nasty "nag" requester.
BTW, the nag requester was unfortunately unavoidable. Probably you know my 
program BootControl? It allowed the use of VGA-only monitors with Amigas, 
even the BootMenu, an interrupted startup-sequence or Guru Meditations 
were visible. It offered some other features, too and a well documented 
API for programmers. It was an experiment - "real" shareware - uncrippled, 
no nag requesters, fully functional. I received ZERO registrations. Not 
even a single one. Only some enhancement requests :-) The experiment 
failed, I would say.
To summarise, yes, IDE-fix was a successful product, but now - after 
Amiga, Inc. announced their plans on the WOA - sales dropped nearly to 
zero, what I can fully understand. I don't know how long I can justify 
further improvement of the IDE-fix product line, as this takes time which 
can be invested in more commercially interesting projects.
The feedback I get back from the users is usually very positive. This 
makes me happy and is a great motivation to continue to support IDE-fix as 
long as possible and as long as required.

CS : Is there anything you would like to say to the Amiga community?

OK : Yes! I want to say "thank you" for supporting the Amiga over all these 
years. You have given me a lot of support and it was and still is a 
pleasure developing products for you! And I hope we will see us again on 
the "Amiga - the next Generation" which will hopefully bring back the 
"Magic" to the Miggy.

CS : Thankyou for your time!

OK : You're welcome!

Why not visit Olivers web site at :-

@{b}http://www.elaborate-bytes.com@{ub}

    @{" Main Menu " link "Main" } @{" Articles Menu " link "arti" }
@endnode

@node "fe2" "Memory"

@{fg shine} The joys of memory@{fg text}

 This is a short article to explain the joys of purchasing more memory 
for your Amiga. The benefits and troubles that you may encounter on 
your travels into the unknown, ahem.. on with the article.

 Up until about 2 months ago I had 8mb of memory which I purchased with 
my Blizzard 030 board in about January 1998. That was a step up as until 
then I only had 4mb, what a saviour having 8mb was... well at least 
until I did web browsing seriously. 8mb was enough but when you want to 
use a web browser the cache can build up quite quickly leaving you one 
of two options, you could either keep emptying it wasting time or buy 
more memory. Emptying the cache is a rather sneaky way of saving 
yourself some cash but it not always the best solution. There is the 
benefit of saving money but are you really saving money when you have 
to stop to delete all the pictures and html code that has built up, 
this takes time and phone bills are still running while you do this. 
Ok, its not so much time but just clearing your cache doesn't solve all 
the problems and you don't get all your memory back so after a while you 
find your computer will be run down and out of memory, windows will 
open slowly and the drawing will seem stupid, you carry on scraping for 
some more memory until your computer fails and gurus out, click, your 
modem goes offline and you have to login again.

 Maybe for alot of you that isn't so much trouble but just think if you 
had that little extra memory you could do many more things. I was in 
this situation and it was time to upgrade, out came the slightly empty 
wallet and then came the credit card ;) ah the wonders of today, eh?

 Looking through the main print magazines like Amiga Format and the late 
CU Amiga I decided that 32mb was the size that I required. I looked around
for the cheapest company and found that Blittersoft was going to inherit
my memory upgrade money, I hadn't had any experience with Blittersoft 
before so it was a wait and see affair. Eyetech would have been my choice 
for there excellent service but they where quite a bit more expensive and 
cash is not always rolling around the AIO nerve centre. I phoned up  
Blittersoft to place my order and got that 'happy' feeling you get when 
you spend some of that money you work so hard for, or in this case the 
money you pay off your credit card with ;)

 1 week went by and no simm which was to be expected.... then 2 weeks. By 
then I decided to give Blittersoft a ring to see where the simm had got 
to and got the usual reply that it was all ready to go and would be with 
me tomorow, well I waited and waited, another call to Blittersoft got me 
the same response so I waited some more, 3 weeks after I had placed the 
order it appeared. A little unhappy with Blittersoft I was glad to finally 
get my simm, making a mental note to pay the extra and use Eyetech who do 
get you things on time I rushed up stairs to get the memory in, it was a 
simple job of just clipping the simm into the correct place and that was 
it, I now had the power at my fingertips.

 On went the computer displaying lots of lovely memory. Great! web browsing 
that didn't crash, can keep the cache without deleting all the files so I 
can browse my favorite pages while offline and overall the computer is 
slightly faster, not much but there is some small speed increase and now 
I can have AmIRC, AWeb, AmiFTP, Yam plus a host of other programs including 
Dopus, A few IRC bots running for certain people on a host of IRC channels 
and I can now host at least 60+ people when I run my experimental irc 
server, considering it'd be a push to run AmIRC, Yam and a web browser 
with 8mb I am totally happy with my purchase.

 Overall I recommend that everyone gets extra memory and slaps it into their 
amigas, it opens a whole new world, ok my computer system isn't a real
power beast but add 32mb and you can do many things you never dreamed of 
doing before. I say make the upgrade, 16mb you may get by with but 32mb 
is really what I would say go for, you could have 32mb for around £40 and 
that includes p&p.

 Note : If you haven't upgraded your computer processor and still have the
standard that came with it you have to buy a ram board aswell as the simm
so that can boost the price by a big margin, If this is your situation
I suggest buying an 030 with 32mb on it, it will cost you pretty much the
same price and your computer will be super fast compared to your old
processor.

